      <h2>Twitter Trademark and Content Display Policy</h2>
      <p class="intro">This policy is designed to help you use our brand and assets, including our logo, content and trademarks without having to worry about negotiating a separate agreement with us or talking to our lawyers. If you’d like to make any use of our marks that is not covered by this document, you must contact us at trademarks at twitter.com and include a visual mockup of intended use.</p>



      <h3 id="twitter-birds">
        Using the Twitter brand and trademarks
        <a class="brand-permalink" href="#twitter-birds" title="Link to this section">&infin;</a>
      </h3>
      <img alt="" class="brand-resources-bird-callout" src="https://si0.twimg.com/a/1360875635/images/resources/twitter-bird-callout.png" />
      <p>Twitter’s marks include, but are not limited to, the Twitter name, logo, Tweet, Twitter bird, and any word, phrase, image, or other designation that identifies the source or origin of any of Twitter’s products.</p>
      <p>Do not modify or alter the marks or use them in a confusing way, including suggesting sponsorship or endorsement by Twitter, or in a way that confuses Twitter with another brand.</p>
      <h4>Downloads</h4>
      <div class="twitter-bird-logos">
        <div class="bird-logo-option">
          <span class="twitter-bird-example transparent-bird">
            <img alt="" class="" src="https://si0.twimg.com/a/1360875635/images/resources/twitter-bird-light-bgs.png" />
          </span>
          <strong>For light backgrounds</strong>
          <a href="/images/resources/twitter-bird-light-bgs.eps">EPS</a> <span class="separator">&middot;</span> <a href="/images/resources/twitter-bird-light-bgs.png">PNG</a>
        </div>
        <div class="bird-logo-option">
